>But look at
>what they are saying right now: Loadable device drivers... "soon",

No.  Loadable device drivers *now*.

>Drag and drop... "R6 is out any day now", 

Again, depends on the application.  I'm not one to hold my breath for X11R6,
though.

>Running ODS apps...
>"emulator is coming along nicely", Running Winodws apps... "WABI is
>almost here", ..etc. ..etc. What a joke!

WABI was started in *June*, ferchrissake!!  What do you expect in a couple
of months?  And yet, the reports say that it already runs a respectable
subset (though not enough to run a major Windows application).

>Observation #4:
>Linux is inferior to DOS! How's that? Well, DOS has loadable device
>drivers, linux doesn't. 

Wrong again.

>Your printer and modem use the same IRQ? No problem in Windows, just don't
>use them at the same time. In linux,
>you have to use the modem a little, stop, recompile the kernel with
>the printer enabled and the modem disabled, use the printer a little,
>stop, recompile, use the modem, stop, ...etc. Two drivers that use the
>same IRQ cannot live in the same kernel, even if none of them is used!

Such is the nature of true multitasking, though this *can* be fixed....

>Observation #5:
>Not only that linux doesn't support drag an drop, its users have no
>concept of what drag and drop is! Most of them think it's just cut and
>paste, as can be seen clearly in the "rebuttals".  The only way to get
>drag and drop in linux is to pay $299 (NT is less expensive, how
>ironic) to buy Motif, 

$199, bozo.

>and virtually no Motif application makes use of
>it anyway, and you cannot drag and drop between Motif and Xaw
>applications.

Right.  X is lacking an integrated GUI.  It was designed that way explicitly.
Maybe this was a mistake, maybe it wasn't.  Either way, if you absolutely
must have drag and drop across the board, then Linux isn't for you.

>Observation #6:
>Linux users have no idea what multimedia support is.  Multimedia
>support is NOT that the os is able to talk to a sound card!  DOS can
>do that. It is that the os has inherent layering facilities to do
>multimedia. To run a full motion picture clip or play a MIDI song via
>the sequencer in Windows, you just call a single API function (e.g.
>MciSendCommand).

Why would you want this built into the KERNEL???  There are better
generalizations than that, e.g. a real-time filesystem and real-time
scheduling.

>Observation #7:
>QIC-80 support is not in linux, nor is it ever likey to be. 

Didn't you already say this?

>The general consensus among linux developers is that QIC-80 is simply
>unsuitable to multitasking environments, a claim that's obviously
>disproved by NT's support for QIC-80.

General consensus?  By whom?  *What* linux developers?

BTW, how well does the NT QIC-80 driver do when there are other background
tasks going?  Does it stream anyway?  How badly are the applications hit?

>Observation #8:
>Q: What does linux do when it runs low on memmory? A: IT FALTERS! The
>only os I have seen that locks up when it runs low in memory. Every
>linux user must constantly watch for memory useage, if linux needs a
>few more kilobytes than are available, it doesn't complain, it just
>crawls to a halt before dying a miserable death, taking down the whole
>system with it.

An unfortunate consequence of making the most of what you've got.  :-)

Of course, if you *really* don't like it, you can fix it.  You have the
source.

I'd *love* to see you fix something you don't like about NT.  Just try.
Heh heh heh.

>Need I say more? There is still lots to talk about: the flaky file
>system, 

*What* flaky filesystem?  All of the filesystems in use *now* are rock-
solid reliable.

>the feeble networking, ..etc. ..etc.

Feeble networking, eh?  You mean things like the ability to mount filesystems
via NFS?  Telnet?  FTP?  That kind of networking?  Flaky indeed.

From reading the newsgroup, it looks like the only networking problem Linux
has involves doing rerouting.

>Linux users, get a clue! Your os is shit. 

Oh, sure.  An OS that I haven't been able to crash *once* while doing normal
Unix things.  An OS that's smaller and faster than *any* of the commercial
Unixes out there.  An OS that's smaller than NT (and probably faster, too).

Yup, sounds like a piece of shit to me.  :-)

>And remember, we didn't start this.

Yeah.  Right.

