From: tzs@hardy.u.washington.edu (Tim Smith)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: Get a grip! (was: NT versus Linux)
Date: 21 Aug 1993 02:11:14 GMT

Kevin Brown <kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com> wrote:
>Additionally, a large segment of the Linux crowd is technically competent,
>so bug reports are *meaningful* as opposed to the useless complaints most
>computer-illiterate users generate.

Actually, technically competent testers can be a disadvantage.  There was
a company that developed a video editing system for the Mac.  It was
very expensive (about $5000 or more for the card and software, I believe).
All of their beta testers were professionals in the video editing field.
They loved the product.

When the product got out of beta and was released, a zillion fatal bugs
were found.  What went wrong?

It turns out that when the pros found a bug, they would figure out a work
around, and not be too concerned about it.  They knew that this little
$5000 system was doing things that previously required them to use equipment
costing $100,000 or so, so they expected there to be flaws that they would
have to work around.  To them, it's saving them $95,000 dollars!  So what
if it crashes when they do a certain obscure thing?  For $95,000, they will
just stop doing that obscure thing.  The thing was vastly better than they
expected a $5000 system to be, so they were happy.

--Tim Smith

